## Material parameters
The material parameters used in this repository are compiled from published literature related to plasma arc erosion in SF6 circuit breakers and high-temperature material behavior.


## Reference
Unless otherwise stated, the material parameters used in this work, including density ρ (kg·m^−3), enthalpy H (J·kg^-1), specific heat Cp (J·K^-1·kg^-1), thermal conductivity K (W·m^-1·K^-1), dynamic viscosity η (kg·m^-1·s^-1), and electrical conductivity σ (S/m), are taken from the following references.
[1] Wu, Y., Chen, Z., Yang, F., Cressault, Y., Murphy, A. B., Guo, A., ... & Sun, H. (2015). Two-temperature thermodynamic and transport properties of SF6–Cu plasmas. Journal of Physics D: Applied Physics, 48(41), 415205.
[2] Chervy, B., Gleizes, A., & Razafinimanana, M. (1994). Thermodynamic properties and transport coefficients in SF6-Cu mixtures at temperatures of 300-30000 K and pressures of 0.1-1 MPa. Journal of Physics D: Applied Physics, 27(6), 1193-1206.
[3] Yin, Jianning, et al. "The arcing and post-arc breakdown characteristics of SF6 generator circuit breaker based on magnetohydrodynamic model." Physics of Fluids 36.11 (2024).


## Additional clarification
For properties reported only at discrete temperature points, interpolation or piecewise fitting is used to construct the temperature-dependent functions required by the solver. Some parameters may differ slightly from the original reported values due to unit conversion, interpolation, extrapolation over a limited range, or minor adjustments for numerical stability. Overall, the spline method is recommended.

Please consult the original references for the detailed experimental conditions, measurement methods, and applicability range of each parameter set.
